    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1952-12-08T08:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1952-12-08T08:00:00-05:00" n="1043"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1043">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">645W.74/12–852: Telegram</note>
                <head>No. 1043<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Egypt (<persName corresp="#p_CJ1"
                            type="from">Caffery</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Department of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d1043fn1">Repeated to London as telegram 462, to Khartoum as
                        telegram 29, and unnumbered to the Arab capitals, Paris, Rome, Moscow, and
                        Ankara.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Cairo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1952-12-08T15:00:00+02:00"
                            >December 8, 1952—3 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1385. Brit Amb has appointment with <persName corresp="#p_NGM1">Naguib</persName>
                    Dec 9 to resume Sudan discussions.<note n="2" xml:id="d1043fn2">In telegram 1403
                        from Cairo, Dec. 10, not printed, Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_CJ1"
                            >Caffery</persName> reported that Stevenson and <persName
                            corresp="#p_NGM1">Naguib</persName> at their meeting on Dec. 9 had
                        reached agreement on a number of points with the result that the British
                        Embassy in Cairo had telegraphed the text of a proposed draft agreement
                        based on the Egyptian note of Nov. 2 to London. (641.74/12–1052)</note>
                </p>
                <pb facs="0204" n="1906" xml:id="pg_1906"/>
                <p>Re London’s tel 3164, Dec 5,<note n="3" xml:id="d1043fn3">Not printed.</note>
                    Brit EmbOff today pointed out that GovGen’s special responsibility towards south
                    is only real stumbling block remaining. He remarked that <persName
                        corresp="#p_NGM1">Naguib</persName> himself appeared appreciate force of
                    Brit position re south and Egypts are prepared to agree to GovGen’s special
                    powers but insist that no public mention thereof be made.</p>
                <p>Brit plan leave question of south until last, meanwhile tying up on other points
                    still at issue.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_CJ1">
                            <hi rend="strong">
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Caffery</hi>
                            </hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
